Barrister Aishatu Muhammad Dantsoho, the Permanent Secretary, Sokoto state Ministry for Women and Children Affairs has said the state is considering opening a sex offenders register to serve as deterrent for would be perpetrators Dantsoho, who spoke at a one day media engagement meeting organised by the ministry with support from Spotlight Initiative stressed that opening such register will go a long way in supporting the campaign towards ending gender based violence. The engagement themed, “streghening Partnership with the Media to Better Promote the Availability of Reporting and Access to Essential Services for Survivors of Violence Against Women and Children” raised amongst other issues the need to have a comprehensive record of all GBV in the state. According to Barrister Aishatu Muhammad Dantsoho,  the unending rise in the cases of Sexual Gender Based Violence (SGBV), Violence Against Women and Girl Child, (VAWGC), harmful practices and all other forms of inhuman treated meted to women and children lately calls for collective concern. Speaking earlier on “Child Rights/GBV Reporting: Ethical Response From the Media” Ankeli Emmanuel stressed that media practitioner as agents of social and behavioral change should do more in following up with GBV to ensuring it’s logical conclusions. According to Ankeli, hence the media sets agenda, a proper dedication to reporting the menace of rape, exploitation, violence, abuse, and subjection to harmful practices will help in restoring a sane society. Ankeli further admonished journalists to adhere strictly to the ethical considerations in reporting about GBV, VAWGC and all other abuses. On her part, Barrister Rashidat Mohammed, delivering paper on “GBV in Nigeria: An Overview of the Situation in Sokoto State and its Impact”, said gender based discrimination often gives rise to low esteem on the part of the survivors. Rashidat insisted that the girl childlike their male counterparts has the right to be empowered, educated, cared for and treated with dignity. According to her, certain obscure cultural believes often encourage GBV, VAWGC in the state and beyond.